Feature: lead-architect template requires the dispatch text to carry observable evidence the lead-held / mailbox @scenario_hash enumeration ran — every conflicting hash named by ID or carrying an explicit retirement instruction

  Supersedes scenario 95 (features/templates/95-lead-architect-dispatch-text-must-name-conflicting-bc-scenario-hashes-or-explicit-retirement.gherkin). The Implementer must locate the BC-side hash of scenario 95 in the shopsystem-templates feature surface and retire that hash when landing this scenario.

  Scenario 95 pinned that the dispatch text resulting from the @scenario_hash enumeration must carry observable evidence the discipline ran — every conflicting BC-side @scenario_hash named by its hash ID or carrying an explicit retirement instruction — and that the architect cite the enumeration "in the same shape that the existing behavior-verification step is cited." The dispatch-text-must-carry-evidence property survives unchanged. Two references re-ground per ADR-018: (1) the conflicting @scenario_hash entries are established from the lead-held "features/" surface and the BC's mailbox-reported register (ADR-018 D1/D2), not from a clone grep; and (2) the "behavior-verification step" cited in the same shape is now the contract-surface verification step (ADR-018 D1), since reading or running BC implementation is no longer admissible. This scenario re-grounds the pin accordingly.

  @scenario_hash:022294afc87e1471
  Scenario: lead-architect template requires the dispatch text to reference each conflicting @scenario_hash entry (established from the lead-held features/ surface and mailbox-reported register) by its hash ID or carry an explicit retirement instruction, cited in the same shape as the contract-surface verification step
    When I read the lead-architect template via "shop-templates show lead-architect"
    Then the content directs the architect that, for any dispatch that retires, supersedes, or contradicts prior BC-side coverage, the dispatch text must reference each conflicting @scenario_hash entry — as established from the lead-held "features/" surface and the BC's mailbox-reported register — by its hash ID, or carry an explicit retirement instruction for that hash
    And the content frames that requirement as the observable evidence the BC Implementer can use to confirm the architect ran the enumeration step, rather than as optional context for the BC
    And the content directs the architect to cite the enumeration in the dispatch description in the same shape that the contract-surface verification step (ADR-018 D1) is cited, so the Implementer does not have to re-derive the conflicts the architect missed
